Parameter tuning: consensus index method

Let's use the consensus index method to determine the best value for "eps" (the maximum distance between neighbor samples and core samples for those neighbor samples to be considered part of the cluster).

In[12]:
n_reps = 20
eps_vals = np.linspace(0.10, 0.90, 20)

stability_scores = []
all_labels = []

for eps in eps_vals:
    labels_list = []

    # repeat DBSCAN
    for _ in range(n_reps):
        model = DBSCAN(eps=eps).fit(X)
        labels_list.append(model.labels_)

    all_labels.append(labels_list)

    # compute pairwise ARI
    ari_values = []
    for lbl1, lbl2 in itertools.combinations(labels_list, 2):
        ari_values.append(ari(lbl1, lbl2))

    # mean ARI for this eps = stability score
    stability_scores.append(np.mean(ari_values))
In[13]:
# Visualize stability scores
plt.plot(eps_vals, stability_scores, marker=".", linestyle="-", markersize=8)
plt.xlabel("'eps' value")
plt.ylabel("Stability Score")
plt.grid(True)
plt.xticks(np.round(eps_vals, 2))
plt.title("DBSCAN 'eps' values stability analysis")
plt.show()

After completing this analysis and seeing the results, I realize that the stability score is the wrong way to assess this parameter. DBSCAN is a deterministic model, so the same X and eps value will produce the same output every time. I will move on to the elbow method.

Parameter tuning: elbow method

Initial parameter exploration

In[14]:
# Use elbow method to visualize silhouette score values for different eps values

eps_vals = np.linspace(0.10, 0.90, 10)
sil_scores = []

for eps in eps_vals:
    model = DBSCAN(eps=eps).fit(X)

    labels = model.labels_
    # Silhouette cannot be computed with 0 or 1 clusters
    if len(set(labels)) <= 1 or (len(set(labels)) == 2 and -1 in set(labels)):
        sil_scores.append(np.nan)
    else:
        sil_scores.append(silhouette_score(X, labels))

I do not see a clear "elbow." What's more, the silhouette score ranges from 1 to -1, with 1 being the best score, and none of these eps values seem to be yielding a particularly high score.

Let's look at how many clusters are being identified, and what fraction of samples are being assigned to clusters (rather than being unassigned aka designated as noise), for each eps value.

Cluster analysis by eps value

In[20]:
eps_vals = np.linspace(10, 60, 30)

num_clusters = []
cluster_fraction = []

for eps in eps_vals:
    model = DBSCAN(eps=eps).fit(X)
    labels = model.labels_

    counts = Counter(labels)

    # Identify real clusters (exclude noise label -1)
    cluster_labels = [lab for lab in counts.keys() if lab != -1]

    # Number of clusters
    num_clusters.append(len(cluster_labels))

    # Fraction of points assigned to a cluster (not noise)
    n_clustered = sum(counts[lab] for lab in cluster_labels)
    frac = n_clustered / len(labels)
    cluster_fraction.append(frac)

    print(f"eps={eps:.2f} | clusters={len(cluster_labels)} | clustered fraction={frac:.3f}")

There is no visible "elbow," so I will have to assess the tradeoff between number of clusters and fraction of samples clustered. Subjectively, I will choose an eps value of 35.8, which has 10 clusters and a little less than 70% sample assignment to a cluster.

Visualize with PCA

Visualize the DBSCAN clustering results with eps=35.8 using PCA to compare cluster assignments with true tissue types.

In[26]:
# Import additional libraries needed for visualization
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from matplotlib.patches import Patch

# Train DBSCAN model with eps=35.8
dbscan_model = DBSCAN(eps=35.8).fit(X)
dbscan_labels = dbscan_model.labels_

print(f"Number of clusters: {len(set(dbscan_labels)) - (1 if -1 in dbscan_labels else 0)}")
print(f"Number of noise points: {list(dbscan_labels).count(-1)}")
print(f"Fraction of samples clustered: {(len(dbscan_labels) - list(dbscan_labels).count(-1)) / len(dbscan_labels):.3f}")

In[27]:
# Perform PCA for visualization 
pca = PCA(n_components=2)
data_pca = pca.fit_transform(X)

# Map tissue types to numerical values for coloring
tissues = data["Tissue"].unique().tolist()
tissue_to_num = {t: i for i, t in enumerate(tissues)}
tissue_numbers = data["Tissue"].map(tissue_to_num).tolist()

# Use a colormap with enough distinct colors
cmap = plt.cm.get_cmap("tab20", len(tissues))

# Create legend handles for tissue types
legend_handles = [
    Patch(facecolor=cmap(i), label=tissues[i])
    for i in range(len(tissues))
]

In[28]:
# Compare DBSCAN cluster assignments and tissue types in PCA space
# Create subplots
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(20, 8))

# Plot 1: Colored by DBSCAN cluster assignments
# Handle noise points (label -1) separately
scatter1 = ax1.scatter(
    data_pca[:, 0], data_pca[:, 1],
    c=dbscan_labels, cmap="tab10",
    s=30, alpha=0.8, edgecolors='black', linewidth=0.3
)
ax1.set_title("DBSCAN Cluster Assignments (eps=35.8) in PCA Space", fontsize=14)
ax1.set_xlabel("PC1", fontsize=12)
ax1.set_ylabel("PC2", fontsize=12)
cbar1 = plt.colorbar(scatter1, ax=ax1)
cbar1.set_label("Cluster Label (-1 = Noise)", fontsize=12)

# Plot 2: Colored by tissue types
scatter2 = ax2.scatter(
    data_pca[:, 0], data_pca[:, 1],
    c=tissue_numbers, cmap=cmap,
    s=30, alpha=0.8, edgecolors='black', linewidth=0.3
)
ax2.set_title("True Tissue Types in PCA Space", fontsize=14)
ax2.set_xlabel("PC1", fontsize=12)
ax2.set_ylabel("PC2", fontsize=12)

# Add tissue type legend to the second plot
ax2.legend(handles=legend_handles, bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc="upper left", title="Tissue Types")

plt.tight_layout()

# Save the plot
plt.savefig(os.path.join(DBSCAN_OUTPUTS, "DBSCAN_cluster_assignments_PCA.png"))

plt.show()
